{{Infobox person | name = Kate Bishop | image = Kate Bishop.jpg | imagesize = 215px | caption = | birth_name = Kate Bishop | birth_date = 1848 | birth_place = [[Bristol]], [[England]], UK | death_date = 12 June 1923 (aged 75) | death_place = [[London]], [[England]], UK | occupation = Actress | years_active = | spouse = Lewis J. Löhr (1 child) | children = [[Marie Lohr]] }}
'''Kate Bishop''' (1848 – 12 June 1923) was an English [[actress]] from [[Bristol]], a member of a theatrical family. Her brother and daughter were also successful actors. Her greatest success was in ''[[Our Boys]]'', which ran for more than four years in London. She temporarily retired from the theatre in the late nineteenth century, and returned to play character roles in the early years of the twentieth century.
==Biography== Bishop was born into a theatrical family, the daughter of Charles Bishop. She began acting as a [[Child actor|child]] in [[Bristol]] in 1863.<ref name=times>''[[The Times]] obituary notice'', 13 June 1923, p. 14</ref> Her brother Alfred also successfully entered the theatrical profession.<ref>''The Times'', 23 May 1928, p. 23</ref>
===Career=== In 1868, Bishop appeared with [[Edward Askew Sothern]] in a revival of ''[[Our American Cousin]]'', in which ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'' thought her "arch" but "lacking in dignity".<ref>''The Manchester Guardian'', 24 August 1868, p. 2</ref> In the [[West End theatre|West End]] she appeared in ''A Loving Cup'' at the [[Royalty Theatre]] in 1869,<ref>''The Times'' 10 February 1869, p. 7</ref> and in 1871 at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in a succession of three new plays by [[W. S. Gilbert]], playing Edith Temple in ''[[Randall's Thumb]]'',<ref>''The Times'', 27 January 1871, p. 6</ref> Pipette in ''[[Creatures of Impulse]]'',<ref>''The Times'', 19 April 1871, p. 8</ref> and Jessie Blake in ''On Guard''. Of her performance in the last, ''[[The Times]]'' commented, "The notion of the irresistible flirt is completely realized by Miss Kate Bishop."<ref>''The Times'', 6 November 1871, p. 10</ref> Bishop played in ''About Town'' by Bertie Vyse in 1873<ref>''The Times'', 16 May 1873, p. 7</ref> and ''Ruy Blas Righted'' and ''Romulus and Remus'', both by [[Robert Reece]], in 1874.<ref>''The Times'', 7 January 1874, p. 8</ref><ref>[http://www.picturehistoryprints.com/product/id/19988 Picture History]. Retrieved 20 May 2009</ref>
Her most famous stage role was Violet Melrose in [[H. J. Byron]]'s ''[[Our Boys]]'', which she created in January 1875 and played practically continuously throughout its historic run of four years and four months.<ref name=times/> When ''Our Boys'' finally closed, it was by far the longest-running work of theatre up to that time.<ref>Booth, Michael R. Review of plays by H. J. Byron including ''Our Boys'' in ''The Modern Language Review'', Vol. 82, No. 3, pp. 716-17 (July 1987; Modern Humanities Research Association)</ref> Byron supplied a successor, ''The Girls'', in which Bishop had another leading role.<ref>''The Times'', 21 April 1879, p. 12</ref> Family life in Australia took her away from the English stage for some 15 years at the end of the nineteenth century.<ref name=times/> In 1900 she returned to the stage in ''[[Struwwelpeter]]'', at the [[Garrick Theatre]], together with [[George Grossmith Jr.]]<ref>''The Times'', 27 December 1900, p. 8</ref> She played Mrs Percival de Hooley in [[Jerome K. Jerome]]'s ''The Passing of the Third Floor Black'' in 1908.<ref>''[[The Observer]]'', 6 September 1908, p. 5</ref> In 1909 she appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in ''Penelope'', by [[Somerset Maugham]], at the [[Lyceum Theatre (Broadway)|Lyceum Theatre]]. Her last stage appearance was in 1915, as Lady Matilda Rye in [[Horace Annesley Vachell|H. A. Vachell's]] ''The Case of Lady Camber'' at the [[Savoy Theatre]].<ref>''The Manchester Guardian'', 13 June 1923, p. 15</ref>
===Personal life=== In 1885, Bishop married Lewis J. Löhr, [[treasurer]] of the [[Melbourne]] [[Opera House]].<ref name=times/> Five years later their daughter [[Marie Lohr]], later a leading actress, was born in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref>Gillan, Don. [http://www.dgillan.screaming.net/stage/th-frames.html?http&&&www.dgillan.screaming.net/stage/lohr/lohr-m3.html Lohr] at the Stage Beauty website. Retrieved 20 May 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.answers.com/topic/marie-lohr-1 Answers.com] Retrieved 20 May 2009</ref>
Bishop died in London, aged 75,<ref name=times/> and is buried in [[Brompton Cemetery]].{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}
